Dan Omwansa, one of the pioneer Kenyan athletes was buried on Friday in a solemn ceremony at his Ibeno home in Kisii County. Omwansa who was born in died at Nakuru Provincial Hospital two weeks ago after a long illness. He left behind two widows and 13 children. He was a Kenya Defense Forces officer and later joined the Postal Corporation of Kenya. Hundreds of mourners among them Athletics Kenya officials, retired and active athletes attended the burial service which was held at Nyanturago Stadium in Nyaribari Chache constituency. Athletics  Kenya Nyanza South chairman Peter Angwenyi represented AK President Jackson Tuwei. Angwenyi read Tuwei’s message of condolences to the family. “On behalf of Athletics Kenya, executive committee and the entire athletics fraternity we wish to convey our sincere heartfelt condolences to the family and relatives during this trying moment,” Tuwei said. On his part, Angwenyi said Omwansa’s death was a big loss to the athletics fraternity. “He was a hero, trailblazing athlete and coach. His death is a big loss,” said Angwenyi. Gusii Sports Legends Association director Alfred Momanyi asked Athletics Kenya to support retired athletes. Retired marathoner Sammy Nyangicha who is also the Gusii Sports Legends Welfare Association vice chairman proposed that Nyanturago stadium be renamed after Omwansa. “This stadium should be upgraded and named after Omwansa. This is one way of honouring a legend,” said Nyangicha. However, President Uhuru Kenyatta in the year 2020 said the stadium will be named after pioneer Kenyan athlete Nyantika Maiyoro. He also announced that a sports talent academy will be constructed. However, the construction is yet to start. Some of the retired athletes who attended the burial were Olympic gold medalist Charles Asati, former world champion Jackline Maranga, Gladys Asiba, Hezron Mokamba, Abel Gisemba, Leonida Omwansa among others.